# PowerShell Shell Rules

The default shell is PowerShell 7. Never invoke `pwsh`, `bash`, or `cmd` explicitly.

## Heredocs Don't Work

PowerShell does not support bash-style heredocs (`<<'EOF'`). For git commit messages:

```powershell
# WRONG — will fail with "Missing file specification after redirection operator"
git commit -m "$(cat <<'EOF'
message
EOF
)"

# CORRECT — use inline string with backtick-n for newlines
git commit -m "Line one`nLine two`nLine three"

# CORRECT — for very long messages, write to a temp file
$msg = "Line one`nLine two"; Set-Content -Path msg.txt -Value $msg; git commit -F msg.txt; Remove-Item msg.txt
```

## Chaining Commands

```powershell
# Use semicolons to chain (runs regardless of previous exit code)
git add .; git commit -m "msg"

# Use && only when you need short-circuit on failure
git add . && git commit -m "msg"
```

## Quoting Paths

Always double-quote paths with spaces. PowerShell uses backtick as escape, not backslash.

```powershell
& "C:\Program Files\Microsoft Visual Studio\18\Enterprise\MSBuild\Current\Bin\MSBuild.exe" "path\to\project.vcxproj"
```

## Listing Files

`ls` in PowerShell returns objects, not plain text. Use `-Name` for names only:

```powershell
Get-ChildItem "path" -Name           # File/dir names
Get-ChildItem "path" -Recurse -Name  # Recursive listing
```
